# Reference accessed: 2026-05-30 via gh api.
#
# nimpretty is the **Nim Pretty Printer** (Nim
# formatter) by the nim-lang team — official Nim
# code formatter built into the Nim compiler.  Pivots
# from C# System.CommandLine (R286 fracjson) into the
# **Nim language tooling cluster**.  Sister to nimble
# (Nim package manager, in corpus), the Nim compiler
# itself.  **MAJOR MILESTONE**: corpus's **first
# documented Nim parseopt CLI** — adds Nim to the
# cross-language CLI taxonomy (26 library variants
# now).
#
# Critical extraction note: nimpretty uses **Nim's
# stdlib `parseopt`** library at `import parseopt`
# — corpus's **first documented Nim parseopt CLI**.
# `parseopt` is **the** standard Nim CLI parsing
# library — built into the Nim stdlib (no nimble
# install needed).  Used by Nim's compiler, nimsuggest,
# nimpretty, koch (Nim build tool), and many Nim CLIs.
# Note: many Nim CLIs use the THIRD-PARTY `cligen`
# library instead, which provides higher-level
# auto-generation from proc signatures (similar to
# alembic's R267 introspection approach).  This round
# documents the LOW-LEVEL stdlib parseopt.  Extends
# the **cross-language CLI taxonomy** to TWENTY-SIX
# library variants: Rust (6), Go (4), Python (3),
# Crystal OptionParser (R269), Haskell optparse-
# applicative (R270), OCaml Cmdliner (R271), C POSIX
# getopt (R272), Java picocli (R276), Kotlin clikt
# (R277), Scala decline (R278), Dart args (R279),
# Ruby OptionParser (R280), Perl Getopt::Long (R281),
# PHP Symfony Console (R282), Swift ArgumentParser
# (R283), F# Argu (R284), Lua argparse (R285), C#
# System.CommandLine (R286), **Nim parseopt** (R287
# — NEW).  **MAJOR PATTERN MILESTONE**: 26 cross-
# language CLI library variants documented.
#
# Critical extraction note: nimpretty uses **ITERATOR-
# BASED parsing** at nimpretty.nim:134 — `for kind,
# key, val in getopt():` is a Nim iterator that
# yields a tuple `(kind: CmdLineKind, key: string,
# val: string)` for each parsed CLI token.
# Documents the **Nim iterator-CLI pattern** — corpus's
# **first documented iterator-based CLI parsing**.
# Distinct from clap derive's struct-population
# (R247+), Click's decorator stack (R266 uvicorn),
# and argparse's `parse_args()` returning a Namespace
# (R267 alembic).  Nim's iterator approach is closer
# to manual parsing (cf. R273 irust hand-rolled) but
# the LIBRARY provides the TOKENIZER.  The developer
# writes the DISPATCH logic via `case kind` +
# `case key`.  This is the **stream-processing CLI
# pattern**: parsing happens INCREMENTALLY as you
# iterate through tokens.
#
# Critical extraction note: nimpretty uses **`cmd*`
# DISCRIMINATOR enum** at nimpretty.nim:136-156 —
# parseopt's `CmdLineKind` enum has 4 variants:
#   `cmdArgument` — positional argument
#   `cmdLongOption` — `--long-name` flag
#   `cmdShortOption` — `-s` short flag
#   `cmdEnd` — end-of-input sentinel
# Used in `case kind` to dispatch handling per token
# type.  Documents the **enum-discriminator parsing
# pattern** — distinct from R275 jiff-cli's lexopt
# `Arg::Short(c) | Arg::Long(name) | Arg::Value(v)`
# enum (R275 used Rust pattern matching) and R272
# blink's getopt() return value (C int with `case`
# dispatch).  Nim's enum is type-safe and exhaustive
# (compiler warns on missing case).  Corpus's
# **first documented CmdLineKind discriminator
# enum**.
#
# Critical extraction note: nimpretty uses
# **MULTIPLE VALUES per case branch** at nimpretty
# .nim:146, 147, 149, 150, 154 — Nim's `case` statement
# supports `of "output", "o", "out":` — a single
# branch matched by ANY of the listed values.
# Documents the **multi-value case-branch pattern**
# in Nim — equivalent to Rust's match `"output" |
# "o" | "out"` (R273 irust) and Crystal's `when "a",
# "b":` (R269 shards).  Plus nimpretty uses
# `of "stdin", "":` to pair `--stdin` with the empty
# string (which corresponds to the bare `-` arg —
# typical Unix idiom).  Corpus's **first documented
# Nim multi-value case-branch CLI dispatch**.
#
# Critical extraction note: nimpretty uses
# **`normalize(key)`** at nimpretty.nim:145 — calls
# Nim stdlib's `normalize` function to lowercase the
# key (and remove underscores) for case-INSENSITIVE
# flag matching.  So `--output` / `--Output` /
# `--OUTPUT` / `--Out_put` ALL match `of "output":`.
# Documents the **case-insensitive flag matching**
# via manual normalization — distinct from clap
# derive's case-sensitive default (R247+), Ruby
# OptionParser's case-sensitive (R280 reek), and
# R260 dua's `ignore_case = true` ValueEnum attribute
# (which is for VALUES, not FLAG NAMES).  Nim's
# approach is MANUAL — the developer calls
# `normalize()` explicitly.  Corpus's **first
# documented manual case-insensitive flag matching**.
#
# Critical extraction note: nimpretty uses
# **`parseopt` UNIVERSAL `key=val` format** at
# nimpretty.nim:148-152 — parseopt accepts BOTH
# `--indent:4` (Nim convention) AND `--indent=4`
# (POSIX convention) AND `--indent 4` (space-separated)
# for value-taking options.  Nim's COLON convention
# (`--indent:4`) is unique to Nim/Pascal-family
# languages.  Documents the **multi-format value-
# separator support** — parseopt is FLEXIBLE about
# how values follow flag names.  Distinct from getopt
# (C, R272 blink — requires `=` or space), clap
# derive (Rust, R247+ — requires `=` or space), and
# argparse (Python, R267 alembic — accepts both).
# Nim/parseopt's `:` separator is a DIALECT-SPECIFIC
# convention but the library also accepts the
# universal `=` and space.  Corpus's **first
# documented colon-separator CLI value format**.
#
# Critical extraction note: nimpretty uses **manual
# `cmdArgument` recursion for directory args** at
# nimpretty.nim:137-142 — when a CLI arg is a
# directory (checked via `dirExists(key)`), nimpretty
# uses `walkDirRec(key, skipSpecial = true)` to
# RECURSIVELY collect all `.nim` and `.nimble` files
# in the directory tree.  Documents the **arg-as-
# directory recursive pattern** — common in
# linters/formatters that accept either files or
# directories (cf. R285 luacheck which accepts both).
# Plus the `addFileExt(".nim")` ensures bare names
# get the `.nim` extension auto-appended.

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line

# Flags decoded source-direct from nimpretty.nim
# lines 144-155.  Multiple aliases per flag via
# Nim's case-of multi-value pattern.
_arguments -s -S \
  '(--help -h)'{--help,-h}'[show help (manual writeHelp proc)]' \
  '(--version -v)'{--version,-v}'[show version (manual writeVersion proc)]' \
  '(-o --out --output)'{-o+,--out=,--output=}'[set the output file (default: overwrite the input file)]:file:_files -g "*.nim"' \
  '(--outDir --outdir)--outDir=[set the output directory (default: overwrite the input files)]:dir:_files -/' \
  '--stdin[read input from stdin and write output to stdout]' \
  '--indent=[number of spaces for indentation (0 = autodetect; case-INSENSITIVE)]:n:(0 2 4 8)' \
  '--maxLineLen=[desired maximum line length (default: 80; alias --maxlinelen due to normalize() call)]:n:' \
  '--backup=[create backup of input (undocumented; bool: on/off)]:bool:(on off true false)' \
  '*:Nim source file or directory (recursively scans .nim and .nimble):_files -g "*.{nim,nimble}"'
